nist-cps pack — content licence
===============================

This pack is derived from:
    Framework for Cyber-Physical Systems:
        Volume 1, Overview        — NIST Special Publication 1500-201
        Volume 2, Working Group Reports — NIST Special Publication 1500-202
        Volume 3, Timing Annex    — NIST Special Publication 1500-203
    NIST (US Department of Commerce), Version 1.0, June 2017

Source licence: Public Domain (US Government work, 17 U.S.C. 105)  (tier 1 — see ../../docs/SOURCE-VETTING.md)
No source-material download link is published (see ../../docs/LICENSING.md).

These three Special Publications are works of the United States Government, prepared
by the National Institute of Standards and Technology, and are therefore NOT subject
to copyright protection in the United States (17 U.S.C. 105). They are in the public
domain: anyone may reproduce, transform, and redistribute them for any purpose,
including commercially, without permission. Attribution to NIST is provided as a
courtesy (see the repository NOTICE), not as a legal obligation. NIST does not endorse
this pack or its authors.

THIRD-PARTY MATERIAL CAVEAT. Although NIST's own text is public domain, the source
documents incorporate, UNDER PERMISSION ONLY, third-party figures and diagrams that
remain the copyright of their owners and are NOT in the public domain. These include,
among others, the Beecham Research machine-to-machine sector map and the ETSI
smart-transportation illustration in Volume 1, and vendor/standards-body figures in
Volumes 2 and 3 (for example a network topology used by permission of
chemicalprocessing.com, and an electric-substation synchronization diagram adapted
from Tournier et al., © 2009 IEEE, used with permission). This pack reproduces NONE
of those figures. It contains only synthesized, transformed reference notes drawn
from NIST's own public-domain prose; where a figure's content is relevant it is
described in original words rather than reproduced.

The CPS Framework also references and draws conventions from ISO/IEC/IEEE 42010
(architecture description) and ISO/IEC/IEEE 15288 (system life-cycle processes), which
remain the copyright of ISO/IEC/IEEE. This pack NAMES those standards and describes,
in original words, how the Framework uses them; it does not reproduce their text.

The source is a Version 1.0 (June 2017) living/draft document; NIST states some
sections were incomplete and that its standards references are exemplary rather than
prescriptive.

